gh imitation, autonomy through tradition, innovation through constraint, and freedom through discipline. It was these practices, and a conversation with the past-not a fruitless obsession with assessment-that nurtured a mind like Shakespeare's. And while few of us can hope to approach the genius of the Bard, we can all learn from the exercises that shaped him.Written in a friendly, conversational tone and brimming with insights, How to Think like Shakespeare enacts the thrill of thinking on every page, reviving timeless-and timely-ways to stretch your mind and hone your words.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aRhetoric, Renaissance. 0aThought and thinkingxStudy and teaching. 7aEDUCATION / Philosophy, Theory & Social Aspects.2bisacsh  aEdward Burger.  aFive Elements of Effective Thinking.  aIsocrates.  aMichael Starbird.  aShakespeare studies.  aTudor education.  abooks for teachers.  aclassical education.  aclose learning.  acommon reads.  acreative teaching.  acreative thinking.  aeducational assessment.  afeatured in Chronicle of Higher Education.  afirst year reads.  agifts for students.  ahumanistic education.  ainspirational books for teachers.  aliberal arts.  alifelong learning.  apedagogy.  apublic speaking.  arhetoric.  arhetorical education.  arhetorical training.  aschool testing.  ateaching for the test.  athe classics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SE